liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Another flight from Tel Aviv carrying Australians has landed in Dubai overnight, according to Foreign Minister Penny Wong. "We are planning an assisted departure flight from Dubai to Perth tonight," she wrote on social media. She added that due to "diminishing demand for dedicated assisted-departure flights", there were no "immediate plans" for more flights from Tel Aviv. "We continue to work with partners to assist the departure of Australians who want to leave Israel or the Occupied Palestinian Territories," she said. "Commercial flights departing Tel Aviv remain available."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: No 'immediate plans' for more flights for Australians from Israel

children.content: Another flight from Tel Aviv carrying Australians has landed in Dubai overnight, according to Foreign Minister Penny Wong.
"We are planning an assisted departure flight from Dubai to Perth tonight," she wrote on social media.
She added that due to "diminishing demand for dedicated assisted-departure flights", there were no "immediate plans" for more flights from Tel Aviv.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Lara Stimpson and Charmayne Allison A group of protestors blocked the entrance to the joint Australian-US Defence facility Pine Gap, near Alice Springs in a pro-Palestinian demonstration this morning. A dozen people holding "Free Palestine" signs were chanting prayers and pro-Palestinian statements, centred around a singular protester who had their arm stuck inside a heavy concrete barrel. It's believed nearly 100 staff and contractors at Pine Gap were prevented from entering the site. Protestor and Central Arrernte man Declan-Furber Gillick said the group had gathered to take a stand against the Australian government's "appalling, shameful hypocrisy" in supporting "Israeli continued domination and occupation" of Palestinian lands. "I reject the assertion that Hamas or any Palestinian group armed or otherwise instigated this war," he said. "These recent responses by Hamas as an organisation are … the direct response to decades and decades and decades of repression of the Palestinian people." Northern Territory police and emergency services attended the scene, directing the protestors off the road, while firefighters used an angle grinder to break the barrel open. The main protester has since been arrested by police.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Pro-Palestinian protesters block entry to Australian-US Defence facility

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: There are explosions audible in the cramped, humid room where Azmi Keshawi shelters with his family in Gaza's southern city of Khan Younis. The bombardments keep coming closer, he says, and they're wreaking death and destruction. Mr Keshawi, his wife, two sons, two daughters and tiny grandchildren are trying to survive inside. They get drinking water in jerrycans from the UN school. It tastes salty. The desalination stations stopped working when the fuel ran out. "How the hell did the entire world just watch and let Israel turn off the water?" says Mr Keshawi, 59, a US-educated researcher at the International Crisis Group, his voice rising with anger. The nights are the hardest, he says. When airstrikes crash nearby and explosions light up the sky, the adults muster what little resolve they have to soothe the children. "Boom!" they yell and cheer when the bombs thunder. The babies laugh. But older kids are terrified. "It's really killing me," Mr Keshawi says. "It really breaks my heart." AP

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Qantas recently announced its chairman Richard Goyder had bowed to shareholder pressure and agreed to leave the troubled airline's board next year, joined by two of his fellow directors — Maxine Brenner and chairwoman of the remuneration committee, Jacqueline Hey,. They have agreed to leave at Qantas' interim result in February, while Mr Goyder will step down ahead of the 2024 annual general meeting — but in Goyder's case some say that is not soon enough. You can learn more about that here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zmopL2u9Nxw But it seems investors still want more board rejuvenation at Qantas. On Wednesday Ms Brenner faced a 17 per cent protest vote against her re-election at Telstra, after proxy firm Institutional Shareholder Services recommended against her because of her concurrent board role at the airline. But what for Todd Sampson? The Qantas board's in-house marketing and public relations expert may be the next target of big investors. Proxy advisor Ownership Matter has recommended Mr Sampson be forced to exit the company at the national carrier's upcoming annual general meeting. While another adviser to institutional investors, ISS, "notes" ongoing concerns about accountability, as well as Sampson's role on the remuneration committee. It will be interesting to see how investors react when the airline holds its annual general meeting at the Melbourne Convention and Exhibition Centre on November 3.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Can Qantas directors like Todd Sampson survive the November 3 AGM?
